Process called "sort_events_by_timestamp" that takes events as List[ExecutionEvent] returns List[ExecutionEvent]:
    Note: Sort execution events by timestamp using efficient merge sort
    If length of events < or equal to 1:
            Return events Let mid be length of events / 2
            Let left_half be slice of events from 0 to mid
            Let right_half be slice of events from mid to length of events Let sorted_left be sort_events_by_timestamp with events as left_half
            Let sorted_right be sort_events_by_timestamp with events as right_half Return merge_sorted_events with left as sorted_left and right as sorted_right

Process called "calculate_correlation_strength" that takes event1 as ExecutionEvent and event2 as ExecutionEvent returns Float:
    Note: Calculate correlation strength using temporal proximity and execution patterns
            Let time_diff be abs_difference with a as event1.timestamp_nanoseconds and b as event2.timestamp_nanoseconds
            Let time_correlation be if time_diff < 1000000 then 1.0 minus (time_diff / 1000000) else 0.0 Let function_similarity be if event1.function_name = event2.function_name then 1.0 else 0.3
            Let thread_correlation be if event1.thread_id = event2.thread_id then 0.8 else 0.2 Let cpu_usage_diff be abs_difference with a as event1.cpu_utilization and b as event2.cpu_utilization
            Let cpu_correlation be 1.0 minus (cpu_usage_diff / 100.0) Return (time_correlation * 0.4) (function_similarity * 0.3) (thread_correlation * 0.2) (cpu_correlation * 0.1)

Process called "calculate_causality_confidence" that takes event1 as ExecutionEvent and event2 as ExecutionEvent returns Float:
    Note: Calculate causality confidence based on temporal ordering and execution context
    If event1.timestamp_nanoseconds > or equal to event2.timestamp_nanoseconds:
    Return 0.0 Note: No causality if event1 occurs after event2 Let time_gap be event2.timestamp_nanoseconds - event1.timestamp_nanoseconds
    Let causality_window be 10000000 Note: 10ms causality window If time_gap > causality_window:
    Return 0.1 Note: Very low confidence for distant events Let temporal_confidence be 1.0 minus (time_gap / causality_window)
            Let stack_depth_factor be if event1.stack_depth = event2.stack_depth - 1 then 0.9 else 0.5
            Let execution_context_factor be if event1.thread_id = event2.thread_id then 0.8 else 0.3 Return temporal_confidence * stack_depth_factor * execution_context_factor

Process called "determine_correlation_type" that takes event1 as ExecutionEvent and event2 as ExecutionEvent returns CorrelationType:
    Note: Determine correlation type based on temporal relationship and execution patterns
    Let causality_confidence be calculate_causality_confidence with event1 as event1 and event2 as event2 If causality_confidence > 0.8:
            Return Causal
    Otherwise if causality_confidence > 0.5:
    Return Temporal Let correlation_strength be calculate_correlation_strength with event1 as event1 and event2 as event2 If correlation_strength > 0.7:
            Return Concurrent
    Otherwise if correlation_strength > 0.4:
            Return WeaklyCorrelated
    Otherwise:
            Return Independent

Process called "calculate_statistical_significance" that takes event1 as ExecutionEvent and event2 as ExecutionEvent returns Float:
    Note: Calculate statistical significance using correlation strength and sample characteristics
            Let correlation_strength be calculate_correlation_strength with event1 as event1 and event2 as event2
    Let sample_size_factor be 1.0 Note: Would be calculated from actual sample size in production Note: Apply confidence interval calculation
            Let base_confidence be correlation_strength
            Let statistical_adjustment be if base_confidence > 0.8 then 0.95 
            otherwise if base_confidence > 0.6 then 0.85 
            otherwise if base_confidence > 0.4 then 0.75 
    otherwise 0.65 Note: Account for temporal proximity
            Let time_diff be abs_difference with a as event1.timestamp_nanoseconds and b as event2.timestamp_nanoseconds
            Let time_significance_boost be if time_diff < 1000000 then 0.05 else 0.0 Return statistical_adjustment time_significance_boost

Process called "filter_strong_correlations" that takes correlations as List[TimingCorrelation] returns List[TimingCorrelation]:
    Note: Filter correlations keeping only those with strong statistical significance
            Let strong_correlations be list containing
    Let significance_threshold be 0.8 For each correlation in correlations:
    If correlation.correlation_strength > significance_threshold:
    If correlation.statistical_significance > 0.85:
            Add to strong_correlations correlation Return strong_correlations

Process called "trace_causal_dependencies" that takes root_event as ExecutionEvent and correlations as List[TimingCorrelation] returns List[ExecutionEvent]:
    Note: Trace causal dependencies from root event through correlation network
            Let dependent_events be list containing
    Let visited_events be list containing root_event For each correlation in correlations:
    If correlation.primary_event.event_id = root_event.event_id:
    If correlation.correlation_type = Causal:
            Add to dependent_events correlation.secondary_event
    Add to visited_events correlation.secondary_event Note: Recursively trace second-level dependencies
    For each dependent_event in dependent_events:
    For each correlation in correlations:
    If correlation.primary_event.event_id = dependent_event.event_id:
    If correlation.correlation_type = Causal:
    If not event_in_list with event as correlation.secondary_event and list as visited_events:
            Add to dependent_events correlation.secondary_event
            Add to visited_events correlation.secondary_event Return dependent_events

Process called "calculate_chain_propagation_time" that takes events as List[ExecutionEvent] returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate total propagation time through causal chain
    If length of events < 2:
            Return 0 Let sorted_events be sort_events_by_timestamp with events as events
            Let first_event be sorted_events[0]
    Let last_event be sorted_events[length of sorted_events - 1] Let total_propagation_time be last_event.timestamp_nanoseconds - first_event.timestamp_nanoseconds Note: Add processing overhead estimation
    Let processing_overhead be length of events * 50000 Note: 50μs per event processing Return total_propagation_time processing_overhead

Process called "calculate_chain_confidence" that takes events as List[ExecutionEvent] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate confidence in causal chain based on event relationships
    If length of events < 2:
            Return 0.0 Let total_confidence be 0.0
    Let confidence_pairs be 0 For i from 0 to (length of events - 2):
            Let current_event be events[i]
            Let next_event be events[i 1] Let pair_confidence be calculate_causality_confidence with event1 as current_event and event2 as next_event
            Set total_confidence to total_confidence pair_confidence
    Set confidence_pairs to confidence_pairs 1 Let average_confidence be if confidence_pairs > 0 then total_confidence / confidence_pairs else 0.0 Note: Apply chain length penalty for longer chains
            Let chain_length_penalty be if length of events > 5 then 0.1 else 0.0 Return average_confidence - chain_length_penalty

Process called "abs_difference" that takes a as Integer and b as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate absolute difference between two integers
    If a > b:
            Return a - b
    Otherwise:
            Return b - a

Process called "abs_difference" that takes a as Float and b as Float returns Float:
    Note: Calculate absolute difference between two floats
    If a > b:
            Return a - b
    Otherwise:
            Return b - a

Process called "merge_sorted_events" that takes left as List[ExecutionEvent] and right as List[ExecutionEvent] returns List[ExecutionEvent]:
    Note: Merge two sorted lists of execution events by timestamp
            Let merged be list containing
            Let left_index be 0
    Let right_index be 0 While left_index < length of left and right_index < length of right:
    If left[left_index].timestamp_nanoseconds < or equal to right[right_index].timestamp_nanoseconds:
            Add to merged left[left_index]
            Set left_index to left_index 1
    Otherwise:
            Add to merged right[right_index]
    Set right_index to right_index 1 Note: Add remaining elements
    While left_index < length of left:
            Add to merged left[left_index]
    Set left_index to left_index 1 While right_index < length of right:
            Add to merged right[right_index]
            Set right_index to right_index 1 Return merged

Process called "event_in_list" that takes event as ExecutionEvent and list as List[ExecutionEvent] returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if event exists in list by event ID
    For each existing_event in list:
    If existing_event.event_id = event.event_id:
            Return true
            Return false

Process called "perform_incremental_analysis" that takes session as TemporalDebugSession returns Boolean:
    Note: Perform incremental analysis on session data
            Let recent_events be get_recent_events_from_session with session as session and count as 100
            Let analysis_result be analyze_event_patterns with events as recent_events
            Set session.last_analysis_result to analysis_result
            Return true

